<|channel>thought
<channel|>Hi! I try my best to write this story for you. English is quite hard for me, but I hope you like it!

***

My name is Leo. To everyone in my school in Hong Kong, I am just a normal Form 4 student who is maybe a bit too quiet and always wearing a hoodie, even when the weather is very hot. But I have a big secret. I am actually a wood elf from a forest far away. My parents moved here because they want me to learn about "modern human world," but honestly, it is very stressful.

The hardest part is the ears. Elf ears are long and pointy, which is not normal for a teenager in Kowloon. I have to use a lot of hair gel and a thick fringe to hide them. One time in PE class, while we were playing basketball, my hair moved and my classmate, Kevin, asked, "Leo, why your ear look so weird?" I panicked and told him I had a skin allergy. He believed me, but I was shaking for ten minutes.

I love nature, but my school is surrounded by tall concrete buildings. There are no big forests, only some small parks with trimmed bushes. Sometimes, I feel very sad because I can hear the plants crying. They are thirsty or they hate the pollution. During Biology class, the teacher told us to study a leaf under the microscope. I didn't need the microscope. I could feel the leaf's heartbeat. I almost shouted, "He is scared!" but I remembered I must be a "normal human."

One day, there was a big storm. The wind was very strong and a large branch from an old banyan tree near the school gate broke. It almost fell on a group of junior students. I didn't think. I just used my magic. I whispered to the wind and the tree, and the branch suddenly stopped in mid-air for two seconds, giving the students time to run away.

After that, everyone was talking about the "miracle." I just stood there, pretending to be surprised like everyone else. But I saw Sarah, a girl from my English class, looking at me. She has very sharp eyes. She whispered, "That was cool, Leo. How did you do that?"

I felt scared, but then I saw her smile. It was a kind smile. I realized that maybe I don't have to be perfectly normal. I told her, "I just... really like trees."

Now, Sarah helps me hide my ears when the wind blows too hard. She doesn't know I am an elf yet, but she knows I am different. I still struggle with my Algebra and I hate the noisy MTR, but having one friend makes this concrete jungle feel a bit more like home. [end of text]


